The '''War on Cancer''' refers to the effort to find a cure for [[cancer]] by increased [[cancer research|research]] to improve the understanding of cancer biology and the development of more effective [[cancer treatments]], such as [[Targeted therapy|targeted drug therapies]]. The aim of such efforts is to eradicate cancer as a major [[cause of death]]. The signing of the [[National Cancer Act of 1971]] by then [[Richard Nixon|U.S. President Richard Nixon]] is generally viewed as the beginning of the war on cancer, though it was not described as a "war" in the legislation itself.<ref name=NCAo71>{{cite web 
| url=http://www.cancer.gov/aboutnci/national-cancer-act-1971/allpages 
| title=National Cancer Act of 1971
| publisher=[[National Cancer Institute]]
| accessdate=2009-08-09
}}</ref> 

Despite significant progress in the treatment of certain forms of cancer (such as [[childhood leukemia]]<ref name=Kersey1997>{{cite journal
| url=http://bloodjournal.hematologylibrary.org/cgi/content/full/90/11/4243
| title=Fifty Years of Studies of the Biology and Therapy of Childhood Leukemia
| last=Kersey
| first=John H.
| journal=Blood
| year=1997
| volume=90
| issue=11
| pages=4243–4251
| pmid=9373234
}}</ref>), cancer in general remains a major cause of death 40+ years after this war on cancer began,<ref name=Kolata2009_04>{{cite news
| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/24/health/research/24cancerside.html
| title=As Other Death Rates Fall, Cancer’s Scarcely Moves
| last=Kolata
| first=Gina
| date=April 24, 2009 
| publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''
| accessdate=2009-06-10
}}</ref> leading to a perceived lack of progress<ref>[http://www.csicop.org/si/show/war_on_cancer_a_progress_report_for_skeptics The War on Cancer A Progress Report for Skeptics] Skeptical Inquirer, Volume 34.1, January / February 2010</ref><ref name=Hughes2006>{{cite journal 
| title=The War on Cancer: An Anatomy of Failure, a Blueprint for the Future  (book review) 
| journal=[[Journal of the American Medical Association|JAMA]] 
| url=http://jama.ama-assn.org/cgi/content/short/295/24/2891 
| author=Hughes R. 
| year=2006 
| volume=295 
| pages=2891–2892 
| isbn=1-4020-3618-3 
| doi=10.1001/jama.295.24.2891
| issue=24}}</ref><ref name=Begley2008>{{cite web 
| author=Sharon Begley 
| url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/157548 
| title=Rethinking the War on Cancer  
| date=2008-09-15 
| work=Newsweek 
| accessdate=2008-10-09}}</ref> and to new legislation aimed at augmenting the original National Cancer Act of 1971.<ref name=KenHutchBillNews>{{cite web
| title=Kennedy, Hutchison Introduce Bill To Overhaul 1971 National Cancer Act
| author=
| url=http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/144105.php
| date=2009-03-30
| accessdate=2009-03-30
| publisher=Medical News Today
}}</ref>
New research directions, in part based on the results of the [[Human Genome Project]], hold promise for a better understanding of the [[genetics|genetic]] factors underlying cancer, and the development of new diagnostics, therapies, [[Cancer#Prevention|preventive]] measures, and early detection ability. However, targeting cancer proteins can be difficult, as a protein can be [[Druggability#Undruggable_targets|undruggable]].

== History ==
{{main|History of Cancer}}
=== National Cancer Act of 1971 ===
The war on cancer began with the National Cancer Act of 1971, a [[United States federal law]].<ref>{{cite web 
| url=http://dtp.nci.nih.gov/timeline/noflash/milestones/M4_Nixon.htm 
| title=Milestone (1971): National Cancer Act of 1971
| work=Developmental Therapeutics Program Timeline
| publisher=[[National Cancer Institute]]
| accessdate=2009-08-09
}}</ref>
The act was intended "to amend the [[Public Health Service Act]] so as to strengthen the [[National Cancer Institute]] in order to more effectively carry out the national effort against [[cancer]]".<ref name=NCAo71 />
It was signed into law by then [[Richard Nixon|U.S. President Richard Nixon]] on December 23, 1971.  <ref>{{cite web 
| url=http://legislative.cancer.gov/history/phsa/1971 
| title=National Cancer Act, Legislative History
| work=Office of Government and Congressional Relations
| publisher=[[National Cancer Institute]]
| accessdate=2009-08-09
}}</ref>

=== NCI Director's Challenge ===
In 2003, [[Andrew von Eschenbach]], the director of the [[National Cancer Institute]] issued a challenge "to eliminate the suffering and death from cancer, and to do so by 2015".<ref>{{cite web 
|url=http://www.cancer.gov/directorscorner/directorsupdate-08-27-2003 
| title=Director's Update: August 27, 2003: Eliminating Suffering and Death from Cancer by 2015: What Should NCI Contribute to the Challenge Goal?  
| accessdate=2008-11-05 
| author=[[Andrew von Eschenbach]] 
}}</ref><!--
--><ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.manhattan-institute.org/html/mpb_01.htm
| title=Eliminating the Suffering and Death Due to Cancer by 2015
| author=Dr. Andrew von Eschenbach
| publisher=[[Manhattan Institute for Policy Research]]
| work=Medical Progress Bulletin, Issue 1
| date=2005-09
| accessdate=2009-06-13
}}</ref><!--
-->
This was supported by the [[American Association for Cancer Research]] in 2005<ref>{{cite web 
| url=http://www.aacr.org/home/public--media/science-policy--government-affairs/testimony/the-house-appropriations-subcommittee-on-labor,-health-and-human-services,-education-and-related-agencies-(2005).aspx 
| title=Written Testimony Submitted to The House Appropriations Subcommittee on Labor, Health and Human Services, Education and Related Agencies 
| author=Margaret Foti, Ph.D., M.D. 
| publisher=[[American Association for Cancer Research|AACR]] 
| date=2005-04-15 
| accessdate=2009-06-13
}}</ref>
though some scientists felt this goal was impossible to reach and undermined von Eschenbach's credibility.<ref>{{cite journal
| last=Kaiser|first=Jocelyn
| journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]
| title=NCI Goal Aims for Cancer Victory by 2015 
| date=28 February 2003
| volume=299|issue=5611|pages=1297–1298 |doi=10.1126/science.299.5611.1297b
| url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/299/5611/1297.2
| accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref>

[[John E. Niederhuber]], who succeeded Andrew von Eschenbach as NCI director, noted that cancer is a global health crisis, with 12.9 million new cases diagnosed in 2009 worldwide and that by 2030, this number could rise to 27 million including 17 million deaths "unless we take more pressing action."<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.cancer.gov/ncicancerbulletin/100609/page4
| title=Global Cancer Control: An Essential Duty
| author=[[John E. Niederhuber]]
| publisher=[[NCI]]
| work=NCI Cancer Bulletin
| date=2009-10-06
| accessdate=2009-11-08
}}</ref>

[[Harold Varmus]], former director of the [[NIH]] and current director of the [[NCI]],<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.cancer.gov/ncicancerbulletin/071310/page2
| title=Harold Varmus Becomes Fourteenth Director of the National Cancer Institute
| author=Bill Robinson
| publisher=[[NCI]] Cancer Bulletin
| date=2010-07-12
| accessdate=2010-08-04
}}</ref><ref name=Varmus2010_scifri>{{cite web
| url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=128568241
| title=Harold Varmus Returns To Politics
| publisher=''[[Science Friday|NPR's Science Friday]]''
| date=2010-07-16
| accessdate=2010-08-04
}}</ref>
held a town hall meeting in 2010<ref>{{cite video
| title=Harold Varmus: NCI Town Hall Meeting (excerpts)
| url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wamffWRIdNQ
| publisher=[[NCI]]
| date=2010-07-12
| accessdate=2010-08-04
}}</ref>
in which he outlined his priorities for improving the cancer research program, including the following: 
# reforming the clinical trials system,
# improving utilization of the NIH clinical center ([[Mark O. Hatfield Clinical Research Center]]),
# readjusting the drug approval and regulation processes,
# improving cancer treatment and prevention, and
# formulating new, more specific and science-based questions.

