== Progress ==
Though there has been significant progress in the understanding of cancer biology, risk factors, [[cancer treatment|treatments]], and [[prognosis]] of some types of cancer (such as childhood leukemia<ref name=Kersey1997 />) since the inception of the National Cancer Act of 1971, progress in reducing the overall cancer [[mortality rate]] has not been great.<ref name=Hughes2006 /><ref name=Kolata2009Advances /> Many types of cancer remain incurable (such as pancreatic cancer<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.cancer.gov/ncicancerbulletin/110309/page2
| title=Pancreatic Cancer Report Urges Changes in Clinical Trials
| date=2009-11-03
| accessdate=2009-11-08
| publisher=[[NCI]]
| work=NCI Cancer Bulletin
}}</ref>)
and the overall death rate from cancer has not decreased alot since the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web 
| url=http://seer.cancer.gov/csr/1975_2005/index.html 
| title=SEER Cancer Statistics Review, 1975–2005, [[National Cancer Institute]]. Bethesda, MD 
| author=Ries LAG, Melbert D, Krapcho M, Stinchcomb DG, Howlader N, Horner MJ, Mariotto A, Miller BA, Feuer EJ, Altekruse SF, Lewis DR, Clegg L, Eisner MP, Reichman M, Edwards BK (eds) 
| accessdate=2008-10-31 }}</ref>
The death rate for cancer in the U.S., adjusted for population size and age, dropped 5 percent from 1950 to 2005.<ref name=Kolata2009_04 />
Cancer is expected to surpass [[cardiovascular disease]] as the leading cause of death in the world by 2010, according to the [[World Health Organization]]'s ''World Cancer Report 2008''.<ref name=Reinberg_WaPo_2008>{{cite news 
| url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/12/09/AR2008120901814.html
| title=Cancer to Surpass Heart Disease as World's Leading Killer
| last=Reinberg
| first=Steven
| date=2008-12-09
| accessdate=2009-08-30
| publisher=[[The Washington Post]]
}}</ref><ref>{{cite book
| url=http://apps.who.int/bookorders/anglais/detart1.jsp?sesslan=1&codlan=1&codcol=76&codcch=26
| title=World Cancer Report 2008
| last=Boyle
| first=P.
| coauthors=Levin B.
| year=2008
| publisher=[[International Agency for Research on Cancer|IARC]]
| pages=512
| isbn=92-832-0423-9
}}</ref>

There is evidence for progress in reducing cancer mortality.<ref name=SciDailyProgress2010>{{cite news
| url=http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/03/100316101556.htm
| title=Progress Has Been Made in War on Cancer, but Still Many Challenges
| publisher=[[Science Daily]]
| date=2010-03-19
| accessdate=2010-03-19
}}</ref> Age-specific analysis of cancer mortality rates has had progress in reducing cancer mortality in the United States since 1955. An August 2009 study found that age-specific cancer mortality rates have been steadily declining since the early 1950s for individuals born since 1925, with the youngest age groups experiencing the steepest decline in mortality rate at 25.9 percent per decade, and the oldest age groups experiencing a 6.8 percent per decade decline.<ref>{{cite journal
| title=The Decline in U.S. Cancer Mortality in People Born since 1925
| first=Eric J. 
| last=Kort
| coauthors=Nigel Paneth, George F. Vande Woude
| date=2009-08-15
| journal=[[Cancer Research (journal)|Cancer Research]]
| volume=69
| issue=16
| doi=10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-09-0357
| pages=6500–5
| pmid=19679548
}}</ref>
Dr. Eric Kort, the lead author of this study, claims that public reports often focus on cancer incidence rates and underappreciate the progress that has been achieved in reduced cancer mortality rates.<ref>{{cite news
| url=http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2009-08/aafc-cmr080609.php
| title=Cancer mortality rates experience steady decline
| date=2009-08-13
| last=Moore
| first=Jeremy
| publisher=[[EurekAlert]]
| accessdate=2009-08-30
}}</ref>

The effectiveness and expansion of available therapies has seen improvements since the 1970s. For example, [[lumpectomy]] replaced more invasive [[mastectomy]] surgery for the treatment of [[breast cancer]].<ref name=WagingWar101 />
Treatment of childhood leukemia<ref name=Kersey1997 /> and [[chronic myeloid leukemia]] (CML) have undergone major advances since the war on cancer began. The drug [[Gleevec]] now cures most CML patients, compared to previous therapy with [[interferon]], which extended life for approximately 1 year in only 20-30 percent of patients.<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/03/science/03conv.html
| title=Researcher Behind the Drug Gleevec: A Conversation with Brian K. Druker, M.D.
| author=[[Claudia Dreifus]]
| publisher=[[The New York Times|NYTimes]]
| date=2009-11-02
| accessdate=2009-11-03
}}</ref>

Dr. [[Steven Rosenberg]], chief of surgery at the [[National Cancer Institute|NCI]] has said that as of the year 2000, 50% of all diagnosed cases of cancer are curable
through a combination of [[surgery]], [[radiation therapy|radiation]], and [[chemotherapy]].<ref name=WagingWar101>{{cite episode
 | title = History of Cancer
 | episodelink = 
 | series = [http://wagingwaroncancer.com/ Waging War on Cancer]
 | serieslink = 
 | airdate = 2009-08-23
 | season = 
 | number = 101}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
| url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0001/02/se.20.html
| title=Millennium 2000: Cancer (transcript)
| publisher=[[CNN]]
| date=2000-01-02
| accessdate=2009-10-15
}}</ref> Cancer surveillance experts have reported a 15.8 percent decrease in the age-standardized death rate from all cancers combined between 1991 and 2006 along with an approximately  1 percent annual decrease in the rate of new diagnoses between 1999 and 2006.<ref name=SciDailyProgress2010 /> A large portion of this decreased mortality for men was attributable to [[smoking cessation]] efforts in the [[U.S.]].

A 2010 report from the [[American Cancer Society]] found that death rates for all cancers combined decreased 1.3% per year from 2001 to 2006 in males and 0.5% per year from 1998 to 2006 in females, largely due to decreases in the 3 major cancer sites in men (lung, prostate, and colorectum) and 2 major cancer sites in women (breast and colorectum). Cancer death rates between 1990 and 2006 for all races combined decreased by 21.0% among men and by 12.3% among women. This reduction in the overall cancer death rates translates to the avoidance of approximately 767,000 deaths from cancer over the 16-year period. Despite these reductions, the report noted, cancer still accounts for more deaths than [[heart disease]] in persons younger than 85 years.<ref>{{cite journal
| url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.3322/caac.20073/full
| journal=CA: a cancer journal for clinicians
| last1=Jemal
| volume=60
| title=Cancer Statistics, 2010
| issue=5
| pages=277–300
| first1=A
| publisher=[[CA Cancer J Clin]]
| last2=Siegel
| first2=R
| last3=Xu
| first3=J
| last4=Ward
| first4=E 
| author9=Jemal A, Siegel R, Xu J, Ward E
| date=2010-07-07
| pmid=20610543
| doi=10.3322/caac.20073
}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.webmd.com/cancer/news/20100708/cancer-death-rates-are-dropping-in-u-s
| title=Cancer Death Rates Are Dropping in U.S.
| author=Bill Hendrick
| publisher=[[WebMD]] Health News
| date=2010-07-08
| accessdate=2010-08-03
}}</ref>

An improvement in the number of cancer survivors living in the U.S. was indicated in a 2011 report by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] and the [[National Cancer Institute|NCI]], which noted that the number of cancer survivors in 2007 (11.7 million) increased by 19% from 2001 (9.8 million survivors). The number of cancer survivors in 1971 was 3 million. [[Breast cancer|Breast]], [[Prostate cancer|prostate]], and [[Colorectal cancer|colorectal]] cancers were the most common types of cancer among survivors, accounting for 51% of diagnoses. As of January 1, 2007, an estimated 64.8% of cancer survivors had lived ≥5 years after their diagnosis of cancer, and 59.5% of survivors were aged ≥65 years.<ref>{{cite web
|title=Cancer Survivors --- United States, 2007
|url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6009a1.htm?s_cid=mm6009a1_w|work=Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report (MMWR)
|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]]
|accessdate=14 March 2011
|pages=269–272
